As Dieter Kr&#228;utl and 04FS said, yes.  The takeaway from the linked article is that the paths used in the require statements should be relative to the controller file or absolute paths, but that the absolute the paths may be determined at compile time in the controller file as follows:

            if( !defined( &#39;ROOT&#39; ) ) { define( &#39;ROOT&#39;, dirname(__FILE__) ); }

            require ( ROOT . &#39;/pages/home_main.php&#39; );

The required/included files that have their own require/include statements, also use ROOT, but should not (re-)define it, so if another file is to be included in the home_main.php file that was in common_code, a sibling of pages, it would look like this:

            require ( ROOT . &#39;/common_code/loadRequiredVars.php&#39; );  

This way ROOT hides the absolute part of the path, and only needs to be edited if the subdirectory structure below controller&#39;s director is changed in some way.

Of course relative paths could be used instead, but they should relative to the controller&#39;s directory, and not as I had the in my question.

